mately hopeful book. The authors describe a unified vision of conservation that binds nature protection, historical preservation, sustainability, public health, civil rights and social justice, and science into common cause—and offer real-world strategies for progress. To be read, pondered, debated, and often revisited, The Future of Conservation in America is destined to be a touchstone for the conservation movement in the decades ahead.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aConservation of natural resourcesxPolitical aspectszUnited States. 0aConservation of natural resourceszUnited States. 0aConservation of natural resources-Political aspects-United States. 0aConservation of natural resources-United States. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  asustainability, environmentalism, environment, nature, conservation, preservation, water rights, climate change, biodiversity, extinction, endangered species, national park service, protection, public health, science, global warming, nonfiction, politics, history, policy, natural resources, land use, development, leadership, lobbying, wildlands, ecology, deepwater horizon, oil spill, hurricane sandy, extreme weather, indigenous people, political advocacy, social justice.1 aJarvis, Jonathan B., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aWilliams, Terry Tempest.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311068858040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226542195423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226542195/original  a978-3-11-068858-0  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles